snippet.textDisplay:
The Knights of Ren didn't matter.
Rey's vision when she touched the lightsaber didn't matter.
Palpatine being thrown down a shaft inside the Death Star didn't matter.
Rose's character didn't matter at all. Jar Jar was more important than Rose.
Snoke didn't matter. No, Palpatine was not part of the plan for this trilogy.
Why would Palpatine reveal himself across the whole universe in the opening crawl?
There being a map to Luke Skywalker didn't matter because he wanted to be left alone.
The Empire being defeated in the original trilogy didn't matter.
Rey finding out that her parents were nobodies didn't matter.
Every single flirtatious line Finn used towards Rey in TFA didn't matter.
Finn's character arc in this entire trilogy was apparently completed in TFA...
Captain Phasma didn't matter. Both Jango Fett and Boba Fett were far more important.
Using hyperspace as a weapon didn't matter anymore. Low chance of it working? BS!
One thousand Death Stars via super star destroyers sounds like awful fan fiction.
Viewers should have known in past movies that Rey is the granddaughter of Palpatine.
Is Rey really the biological granddaughter of Palpatine? Were those her foster parents?
Luke and Leia knowing about Rey's lineage the whole time was stupid.
Where did the huge Rebel fleet come from? It looks dumb after watching TLJ.
Anakin's redemption in Return of the Jedi is now undermined and anti-climactic.
The Jedi dying in the prequels is undermined because of the concept of force healing.
Force healing was decanonized because it was part of Legends, which is not canon.
Luke died a soulless, angry coward. They can clone Palpatine, but not Luke or Snoke?
Leia flying through space looks even worse. When was she trained? Why didn't we see it?
TIE fighters and smaller fighter ships can't use light-speed. This is lore breaking...
Force ghosts can't physically touch animate or inanimate objects, such as lightsabers.
Force ghosts can't magically cast down lightning from the sky...
Viewers never received a logical explanation on how Maz acquired Luke's lightsaber.
The main characters not knowing about stormtroopers using jetpacks was stupid.
Using Jedi mind-tricks is so inconsistent. Why didn't Rey and Ben use it in TLJ?
Rey's survival at the end was not earned or warranted.
Why did multiple characters need to know Rey's last name in this film? It's not genuine.
If Jedi can use the force as a travel map, why couldn't Rey find the Death Star wreckage?
How would the rebels know about there being a spy in the First Order?
General Hux was a wasted character. There was no point of him being in this film.
General Hux watched billions of people die on three different planets in TFA. Dumb move.
There's so much more.

snippet.textDisplay:
I personally enjoyed the movie but plenty of the criticism is valid. I think the comedy is out of place, Palpatine’s whole role was stupid, it highlights how poorly planned the trilogy was and the absurd retconning of the last movie is idiotic but I still liked it. I think things like the amazing score, the whole arc and character made for Ren and the art direction won me over here.
If I had to compare it to the rest of the franchise I’d say it’s below the other sequels and the original trilogy but a bit above the spinoffs and far above the prequels.

snippet.textDisplay: I just wish Rian Johnson had been given the whole trilogy. snippet.textDisplay:
Maybe I'm just the naive target audience these movies are written for, but I enjoyed this trilogy a lot. Honestly my only complaints were how unconnected they felt but Rey, Kylo Ren, and the waning nature of the Light-side/dark-side ongoing fight felt refreshing. My least favorite part of Episode 9 was honestly how much it tried to forget about/apologize for Episode 8, because that, not the quips and memes, is what takes me out of the experience.
Okay, be honest with me, Star Wars fans, what is it that you want and apparently aren't getting? Because it seems like the loudest voices only like the original trilogy and refuse to admit it (not talking about IHE, I get where you're coming from)

snippet.textDisplay: Why I think the prequels are better is because even though 1 and 2 and even parts of 3 suck, they all build up to something. When Darth Maul and Qui gon/Obi Wan finally duel, we get to see two jedi in their prime against a masterful sith warrior for the first time and it feels exciting. When Anakin kills count dooku, you feel can see what built up to this decision. When Yoda and Palpatine duel, it makes you a 12 year old kid again because that is what you've been waiting six movies to see. When Obi wan stands at the top of a hill and says "You were my brother Anakin. I loved you" it brings a tear to your eye because you saw all of the adventures they had together and how broken they were in the original trilogy. There's real emotion and a lot of memorable moments. There's nothing in the sequel trilogy that makes me feel that way. That's why it's the worst to me.

snippet.textDisplay:
controversial
I completely understand the complaints in this analysis. I genuinely believe that there are a lot of things that this movie could have done better, but I genuinely enjoyed the film. I'm not entirely sure why it sat so well with me, but my general appreciation of this movie comes from its ability to tie not just the new trilogy, but all the movies in. I think people often forget that, in much the same way as the MCU, Star Wars is more a universe than a linear narrative. the ability to create a narrative not just in the characters but in the landscape and the plot itself was really satisfying to me. you see how the wars have affected the landscape. you see how political failures have changed the face of the "bad guys" (admittedly, they have too many names). but even deeper within is the implicit mysticism of the force. Films 1-3 really failed at how the Jedi were portrayed, trying to cram their powers into a neat set of rules rather than allowing the softcore magic to take over. because the Jedi and sith are opposing ideologies. they are symbols, not troops.
in any case, I hope someone got something out of that (:
